Anonymous Thu 17 Nov 2022 12:26:28 No.52409248 Report
Quoted By:
>>52409132
It helps to start small. My first story was a green I wrote in a single 12 hour session that ended up being 3k words. I was into it but I had no idea I would write that much or that it'd take that long and I also didn't account for the proofreading and editing stage either.
While I wouldn't mind writing prose and for longer it's hard to justify the time investment so I instead focus on random greens of 500 words or less. Just zoom in on a scene or 2 and a central point in the story, write that and publish.
I know most in the thread prefer the long stories in the op but that's what I do and I enjoy it. It'd be nice to reach the high levels of the other writers here but it's all fair since they put in all that effort.
From that perspective if you can finish your current work and publish it by all means do that. However if you need a quick start for another story figure out a very basic setting, a character or 2 and 1 key element to write around. Chances are if you like what you're writing you'll make it as long as it needs to be to hit all the points you want.
No idea if that helps though. Good luck with it Anon!

If it makes you feel better, I'm the opposite, and still found my own way here. I had never written anthro characters before, and always had to create my own mythos to even begin to create a story at all. It was an adjustment to do, an experiment, but it's possible to mix and match your comfort levels with regards to a story, with the right inspiration. If you're into established universes already, there's lots of those already that people base their works on, like the snake fans and XCom. There's no rule against writing fanfiction.

As the other anon said, it's probably best to start small when you're out of your comfort zone like this. Try writing a greentext or two, just for yourself, even. You'll find most of the successful greentext-based stories have the main human character is so generic he's literally named Anon, it's like an anime protagonist.

Good luck, anon, there's almost always someone around for advice.

Art quality is matter of piece. A big step in learning art is finding a way around those situational hurdles, where it turns out lopsided half of the time and other times look amazing. One of those is flipping the image, and there's probably others I don't know but I'm bad at teaching myself this shit.
Beginners have a wider range of quality because they haven't figured this shit out yet. Pic related isn't /hmofa/ but it's an example of a major fuckup I did not 24 hours ago. It doesn't look as bad as just lines, but I did finish it, took a step back, looked at it, realized something was off, flipped it and realized it was lopsided as hell. (all I have is wip because I hated it so much I overwrote the png save)
Artists who have been at it longer also get better at picking out flaws, and probably just pickier in general in terms of uploading. Most big dosh patreon kings probably only upload 1/3rd of their work to the public, not everything is shown.
